<?xml version='1.0' encoding='windows-1252'?>
<!--
  WiX Toolset 3.x source for the SourceBox Sentry CloudNode MSI.

  Built by `cargo wix` (which shells out to `candle.exe` and `light.exe`
  from the WiX toolset) and emitted to `target/wix/sourcebox-sentry-cloudnode-
  <version>-x86_64.msi`. The release.yml workflow attaches the MSI to
  the GitHub Release alongside the existing .zip artifact.

  ## Stable identifiers

  - Product/Id="*" — auto-generated per build. Required by MajorUpgrade
    so the new MSI gets a fresh ProductCode.
  - Product/UpgradeCode — IMMUTABLE. Renaming this string for any
    reason will leave existing installs un-upgradeable; an MSI with a
    different UpgradeCode is, from Windows Installer's perspective, a
    completely different product. Generated 2026-04-26 for this
    project; do not change.
  - Component GUIDs — stable across versions so MSI tracks them as
    "the same component" (matters for the service install in
    particular: changing the component GUID on an upgrade can leave
    a duplicate ServiceInstall registration behind).

  ## Service registration

  ServiceInstall registers the service with SCM. Start='demand' (NOT
  'auto') means the service is installed but doesn't try to launch
  itself the moment the MSI finishes — the user runs
  `sourcebox-sentry-cloudnode setup` from an admin console first to write
  config to %ProgramData%\SourceBoxSentry\node.db, THEN starts the service
  manually. Starting before setup would just produce an SCM error +
  log line ("CloudNode is not configured") which is honest but ugly
  for a fresh install.

  We can flip to Start='auto' once the setup wizard reliably writes
  config + (optionally) calls into the SCM API to flip the start type
  itself.

  ServiceControl Stop='both' Remove='uninstall' makes the uninstaller
  clean: stops the running service, then removes the SCM registration
  so a re-install doesn't see a duplicate.

  ## Install scope

  InstallScope='perMachine' — the binary lives under Program Files,
  the service runs as LocalSystem, and config is shared across all
  users on the machine. A per-user install would have meaningfully
  different semantics (per-user service?) and isn't what we want for
  what's essentially server-class software.

  ## What we deliberately don't do

  - **License agreement dialog.** WixUI_Minimal would show one but
    requires a License.rtf and adds a click users mostly skim. Users
    have already seen the GPL-3 LICENSE on GitHub before downloading.
    Add later if a sales context demands it.
  - **PATH modification.** The user can call the binary by full path
    once; after that the installer added a Start menu shortcut they
    can use, OR they Add-Path themselves. Skipping PATH avoids the
    "logout required for env var to take effect" footgun.
  - **Bundled FFmpeg.** FFmpeg is a separate prerequisite documented
    in the README. Bundling would bloat the MSI from ~5 MB to ~80 MB.
-->
<Wix xmlns='http://schemas.microsoft.com/wix/2006/wi'>

    <Product
        Id='*'
        Name='SourceBox Sentry CloudNode'
        UpgradeCode='7B8E5C9A-4D2F-4A1B-9E3C-A0F6D8B25E47'
        Manufacturer='SourceBox LLC'
        Language='1033'
        Codepage='1252'
        Version='$(var.Version)'>

        <Package Id='*'
            Keywords='Installer'
            Description='SourceBox Sentry CloudNode Installer'
            Manufacturer='SourceBox LLC'
            InstallerVersion='450'
            Languages='1033'
            Compressed='yes'
            InstallScope='perMachine'
            SummaryCodepage='1252' />

        <!-- Major-upgrade chain: a newer MSI uninstalls the older one
             before installing itself. Schedule afterInstallInitialize
             is the recommended slot per WiX docs (handles in-flight
             services correctly via the Stop=both we set below). -->
        <MajorUpgrade
            Schedule='afterInstallInitialize'
            DowngradeErrorMessage='A newer version of [ProductName] is already installed. Uninstall it first if you really need to roll back.' />

        <!-- ========================================================
             Wipe %ProgramData%\SourceBoxSentry on real uninstall
             ========================================================
             By default the MSI removes Program Files but leaves
             %ProgramData%\SourceBoxSentry\ in place so an upgrade-
             uninstall (the first half of MajorUpgrade) preserves
             the user's config + recordings. That's correct behaviour
             for upgrades.

             For a *real* uninstall (Settings → Apps → Uninstall, or
             `msiexec /x ...` directly) the user expects "uninstall"
             to mean "gone" — leaving their encrypted node.db with
             API credentials on disk after they explicitly asked the
             OS to remove the program is a privacy footgun.

             v0.1.25 introduced a surgical wipe (delete node.db, hls/,
             logs/, fatal-startup-error.txt; preserve ffmpeg/) so a
             reinstall didn't have to re-download ~150 MB of FFmpeg.
             v0.1.35 deprecated the bundled-FFmpeg story entirely —
             CloudNode now uses the system FFmpeg (winget / brew /
             apt) instead of a private copy under ProgramData. The
             surgical-wipe machinery is no longer needed because
             there's nothing under SourceBoxSentry\ that we want to
             preserve across uninstall:

               - node.db                  → user credentials, wipe
               - hls\                     → rolling video buffer, wipe
               - logs\                    → service logs, wipe
               - fatal-startup-error.txt  → crash report, wipe
               - ffmpeg\                  → no longer created here

             Back to the simple `rmdir /s /q SourceBoxSentry` we
             started with. Cleaner code, no path-resolution edge
             cases, no preserved-state surprises across versions.

             The condition `REMOVE="ALL" AND NOT UPGRADINGPRODUCTCODE`
             is Microsoft's documented idiom for "this is a real
             uninstall, not the uninstall pass of an upgrade." During
             a MajorUpgrade, UPGRADINGPRODUCTCODE is set on the old
             product's uninstall pass, so this CustomAction is skipped
             and the data survives. On Settings → Apps → Uninstall
             (or msiexec /x) UPGRADINGPRODUCTCODE is unset, so this
             fires and ProgramData is purged.

             Implementation:
               - Execute='deferred' Impersonate='no'  → runs in the
                 elevated installer context (LocalSystem), which has
                 write access to %ProgramData%.
               - rmdir /s /q                          → recursive +
                 quiet. /s recurses, /q suppresses prompts.
               - Return='ignore'                      → a stuck file
                 (AV scanning, in-use handle) shouldn't fail the whole
                 uninstall. Better to have the binary gone than to
                 refuse to uninstall over a leftover log. -->
        <CustomAction
            Id='WipeProgramData'
            Directory='APPLICATIONFOLDER'
            ExeCommand='cmd.exe /c rmdir /s /q "[CommonAppDataFolder]SourceBoxSentry"'
            Execute='deferred'
            Impersonate='no'
            Return='ignore' />

        <!-- ========================================================
             Launch setup wizard from the Finish dialog
             ========================================================
             Standard "run app on first install" pattern. The exit
             dialog gets an optional checkbox; if the user leaves it
             checked (default Yes) and clicks Finish, this CustomAction
             fires and spawns the setup wizard in a new console window.

             Why cmd.exe /c start vs invoking the exe directly:
               - `start` detaches the spawned process from the
                 installer's process tree. cmd.exe returns
                 immediately, the MSI install transaction completes
                 cleanly, and the spawned wizard owns its own console
                 window with a meaningful title.
               - Invoking the exe directly via FileKey/ExeCommand
                 would have the wizard inherit the MSI installer's
                 stdin/stdout, which doesn't have a Window Station
                 attached during deferred custom action execution —
                 the TUI's crossterm raw-mode init would fail.

             Impersonate='yes' runs the wizard as the original user
             (the one who clicked Run on the MSI), inheriting their
             elevated token from the UAC prompt that started the
             install. Setup wizard needs admin to write
             %ProgramData%\SourceBoxSentry\node.db, which an admin-elevated
             session can do.

             Return='asyncNoWait' lets the MSI's "Install successful"
             dialog finish promptly without waiting for the wizard to
             exit (which would be many minutes if the user pauses on
             a prompt). -->
        <CustomAction
            Id='LaunchSetup'
            Directory='APPLICATIONFOLDER'
            ExeCommand='cmd.exe /c start "SourceBox Sentry CloudNode Setup" "[#filServiceExe]" setup'
            Execute='immediate'
            Impersonate='yes'
            Return='asyncNoWait' />

        <!-- ========================================================
             One-time cleanup of stale runtime-created residue
             ========================================================
             v0.1.20-v0.1.33 had a bug where SQLite could create
             `Program Files\SourceBox Sentry CloudNode\data\node.db`
             — runtime-created files MSI doesn't know about and
             therefore won't remove on uninstall.  This CustomAction
             nukes that directory on every fresh install so the
             residue can't re-poison `./data` lookups on older
             clients.

             Safe to run unconditionally on v0.1.36+ because the bug
             is fixed (Windows always uses ProgramData now), so the
             directory only exists at all if it's residue.

             TODO(v0.2.0): remove this CustomAction.  By the time we
             cut a 0.2 release the v0.1.20-v0.1.33 install base
             should be gone (those versions can't authenticate
             against current Command Center anyway, since
             MIN_SUPPORTED_NODE_VERSION will have been bumped).

             Return='ignore' so a stuck file (AV, in-use handle)
             doesn't fail the whole install over a leftover artifact. -->
        <CustomAction
            Id='WipeStaleInstallDirData'
            Directory='APPLICATIONFOLDER'
            ExeCommand='cmd.exe /c rmdir /s /q "[APPLICATIONFOLDER]data"'
            Execute='deferred'
            Impersonate='no'
            Return='ignore' />

        <InstallExecuteSequence>
            <!-- On real uninstall, wipe ProgramData. -->
            <Custom Action='WipeProgramData' After='InstallInitialize'>
                REMOVE="ALL" AND NOT UPGRADINGPRODUCTCODE
            </Custom>
            <!-- On every install (fresh or upgrade), nuke any stale
                 `data\` directory residue from v0.1.20-v0.1.33. Runs
                 BEFORE InstallFiles so the directory is clean before
                 the new binary is laid down. -->
            <Custom Action='WipeStaleInstallDirData' Before='InstallFiles'>
                NOT REMOVE
            </Custom>
        </InstallExecuteSequence>

        <!-- ========================================================
             Polished install UI (WixUI_Minimal)
             ========================================================
             Welcome+License combined dialog → Install → Finish.
             "Minimal" is the right scope for our use case: no feature
             selection (we only have one feature), no install-location
             customisation (per-machine install always lands in
             %ProgramFiles%, no good reason to relocate), no advanced
             options. Just enough UI to look like a real product
             instead of a faceless silent install.

             The exit dialog includes the optional checkbox controlled
             by the WIXUI_EXITDIALOGOPTIONALCHECKBOX* properties below.
             A <Publish> element ties the checkbox state to the
             LaunchSetup CustomAction. -->
        <UIRef Id='WixUI_Minimal' />

        <WixVariable Id='WixUILicenseRtf' Value='wix\License.rtf' />

        <Property Id='WIXUI_EXITDIALOGOPTIONALCHECKBOXTEXT'
                  Value='Run setup wizard now (configures Node ID + API key)' />
        <Property Id='WIXUI_EXITDIALOGOPTIONALCHECKBOX' Value='1' />

        <UI>
            <!-- Wire the exit-dialog checkbox to LaunchSetup. The
                 condition gates on the checkbox being set AND this
                 not being a re-install (Installed = empty means
                 first install; Installed = "1" means a repair / MSI
                 re-run, where launching the wizard is unwelcome). -->
            <Publish Dialog='ExitDialog'
                     Control='Finish'
                     Event='DoAction'
                     Value='LaunchSetup'>WIXUI_EXITDIALOGOPTIONALCHECKBOX = 1 and NOT Installed</Publish>
        </UI>

        <Media Id='1' Cabinet='media1.cab' EmbedCab='yes' />

        <!-- Properties surfaced in Add/Remove Programs / Settings → Apps.
             ARPNOMODIFY is intentionally NOT declared here: WixUI_Minimal
             sets it itself (because Minimal has no feature-tree dialog,
             "modify" is a no-op, and the dialog set hides it accordingly).
             Declaring it twice produced LGHT0091 "Duplicate symbol" — see
             the v0.1.21 first-build failure. -->
        <Property Id='ARPHELPLINK'>https://github.com/SourceBox-LLC/opensentry-cloud-node</Property>
        <Property Id='ARPURLINFOABOUT'>https://opensentry-command.fly.dev</Property>
        <Property Id='ARPNOREPAIR' Value='yes' Secure='yes' />

        <!-- ProgramData/SourceBoxSentry/  — runtime config + recordings.
             We don't *create* the folder here (that happens in the
             setup wizard or run_log_cleanup, which already does
             create_dir_all); we only ensure the dir is referenced so
             a hypothetical future RemoveFolder element has somewhere
             to point. -->
        <Directory Id='TARGETDIR' Name='SourceDir'>

            <Directory Id='ProgramFiles64Folder'>
                <Directory Id='APPLICATIONFOLDER' Name='SourceBox Sentry CloudNode'>

                    <!-- Component: the binary + the service registration.
                         Tying these together means the service can't
                         get installed without the exe (or vice versa) —
                         atomic per-component upgrade behaviour. -->
                    <Component Id='cmpServiceBinary'
                               Guid='8C9F6DAB-5E3F-4B2C-AF4D-B1F7E9C36F58'>

                        <!-- Source path matches the GitHub Actions
                             build step (cargo build with the
                             x86_64-pc-windows-msvc target triple),
                             which lands the binary under
                             target\x86_64-pc-windows-msvc\release\,
                             NOT target\release\. cargo-wix does not
                             rewrite this attribute; light.exe reads
                             it verbatim, so the target subdirectory
                             is hardcoded here. The MSI is only ever
                             built on x86_64-pc-windows-msvc; a future
                             ARM64 Windows build would need a wxs per
                             arch or a build-time variable.

                             Binary filename comes from the Cargo
                             package name (sourcebox-sentry-cloudnode).
                             If you rename the package, this Source
                             attribute and the workflow's Compress-
                             Archive command both need updating. -->
                        <File Id='filServiceExe'
                              Source='target\x86_64-pc-windows-msvc\release\sourcebox-sentry-cloudnode.exe'
                              KeyPath='yes'
                              Checksum='yes' />

                        <ServiceInstall
                            Id='svcCloudNode'
                            Name='SourceBoxSentryCloudNode'
                            DisplayName='SourceBox Sentry CloudNode'
                            Description='Streams local USB cameras to the SourceBox Sentry Command Center. Configure with: sourcebox-sentry-cloudnode setup.'
                            Type='ownProcess'
                            Start='demand'
                            ErrorControl='normal'
                            Account='LocalSystem'
                            Arguments='service'
                            Vital='yes'
                            Interactive='no' />

                        <ServiceControl
                            Id='svcCloudNodeControl'
                            Name='SourceBoxSentryCloudNode'
                            Stop='both'
                            Remove='uninstall'
                            Wait='yes' />

                    </Component>

                </Directory>
            </Directory>

            <!-- Start menu shortcut: smart launcher.
                 No `Arguments=` attribute → the binary runs with no
                 subcommand, which hits the bare-invocation path in
                 main.rs. That path checks Config::load for existing
                 credentials and chooses:
                   - creds present → run_cloudnode (foreground TUI
                     dashboard, cameras stream)
                   - creds missing → run setup wizard, then
                     run_cloudnode
                 So the same shortcut handles both first-launch (runs
                 the wizard then streams) and every-launch-after
                 (just streams).
                 The MSI Finish dialog's LaunchSetup CustomAction at
                 the top of this file handles the very first launch
                 after install via cmd /c start with `setup` arg
                 explicitly — that's a separate code path because the
                 Finish dialog needs to spawn a new console window.
                 The shortcut here is what the operator clicks on
                 every subsequent launch; previously it had
                 `Arguments='setup'` which forced the wizard to re-
                 prompt for credentials every single time. v0.1.33
                 dropped the argument so the shortcut becomes a
                 normal app launcher. -->
            <Directory Id='ProgramMenuFolder'>
                <Directory Id='ApplicationProgramsFolder' Name='SourceBox Sentry CloudNode'>
                    <Component Id='cmpStartMenu'
                               Guid='9DAB7EBC-6F4F-4C3D-B05E-C2F8FAD47069'>
                        <Shortcut Id='ShortcutLauncher'
                                  Name='SourceBox Sentry CloudNode'
                                  Description='Launch the CloudNode dashboard. Runs the setup wizard the first time, streams cameras every time after.'
                                  Target='[#filServiceExe]'
                                  WorkingDirectory='APPLICATIONFOLDER' />
                        <RemoveFolder Id='RemoveProgramsFolder'
                                      Directory='ApplicationProgramsFolder'
                                      On='uninstall' />
                        <RegistryValue Root='HKCU'
                                       Key='Software\SourceBox\SourceBoxSentryCloudNode'
                                       Name='installed'
                                       Type='integer'
                                       Value='1'
                                       KeyPath='yes' />
                    </Component>
                </Directory>
            </Directory>

        </Directory>

        <Feature Id='Default'
                 Title='Main'
                 Description='SourceBox Sentry CloudNode service binary and Start menu shortcut.'
                 Display='expand'
                 ConfigurableDirectory='APPLICATIONFOLDER'
                 Level='1'>
            <ComponentRef Id='cmpServiceBinary' />
            <ComponentRef Id='cmpStartMenu' />
        </Feature>

    </Product>
</Wix>
